## 7. **Number of Longest Increasing Subsequence (Leetcode 673)**

**Instinct:**  
Sirf length nahi, count bhi chahiye of all LIS. Har state ke liye (length, count) store karo.

**Approach:**  
1. Memo[i] = {maxLength from i, count}
2. For each j > i where nums[j] > nums[i]
3. Find best length, sum counts

```java
class Solution {
    int[] nums;
    int n;
    Pair[] memo;
    
    class Pair {
        int len;
        int count;
        Pair(int l, int c) { len = l; count = c; }
    }
    
    public int findNumberOfLIS(int[] nums) {
        this.nums = nums;
        n = nums.length;
        memo = new Pair[n];
        
        int maxLen = 0;
        int totalCount = 0;
        
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            Pair p = dfs(i);
            if (p.len > maxLen) {
                maxLen = p.len;
                totalCount = p.count;
            } else if (p.len == maxLen) {
                totalCount += p.count;
            }
        }
        return totalCount;
    }
    
    private Pair dfs(int i) {
        if (memo[i] != null) return memo[i];
        
        int maxLen = 1;
        int totalCount = 1;
        
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if (nums[j] > nums[i]) {
                Pair next = dfs(j);
                if (next.len + 1 > maxLen) {
                    maxLen = next.len + 1;
                    totalCount = next.count;
                } else if (next.len + 1 == maxLen) {
                    totalCount += next.count;
                }
            }
        }
        
        memo[i] = new Pair(maxLen, totalCount);
        return memo[i];
    }
}
```

**Key Insight:** Return pair (length, count). Sum counts when lengths equal.

