## 10. **Number of Subsequences with Sum Mod K**

**Instinct:**  
Subsequences count where sum % k == target. State = (index, remainder).

**Approach:**  
1. Memo[i][rem] = number of subsequences from i with current remainder rem
2. take: (rem + nums[i]) % k
3. skip: same remainder

```java
class Solution {
    int MOD = 1_000_000_007;
    int[] nums;
    int k;
    int[][] memo;
    
    public int countSubsequencesWithSumMod(int[] nums, int k, int target) {
        this.nums = nums;
        this.k = k;
        int n = nums.length;
        memo = new int[n][k];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            Arrays.fill(memo[i], -1);
        }
        return dfs(0, 0, target);
    }
    
    private int dfs(int i, int rem, int target) {
        if (i == nums.length) return rem == target ? 1 : 0;
        if (memo[i][rem] != -1) return memo[i][rem];
        
        int skip = dfs(i + 1, rem, target);
        int take = dfs(i + 1, (rem + nums[i]) % k, target);
        
        memo[i][rem] = (skip + take) % MOD;
        return memo[i][rem];
    }
}
```

**Key Insight:** Modulo arithmetic in state. Track remainder instead of actual sum.

