## 13. **Number of Subsequences with Product Less Than K**

**Instinct:**  
Subsequences count where product < k. Since product can be large, use log or track product directly with pruning.

**Approach:**  
1. Memo[i][product] = count from i with current product
2. If product >= k, stop (pruning)

```java
class Solution {
    int[] nums;
    int k;
    Integer[][] memo;
    
    public int numSubsequenceProductLessThanK(int[] nums, int k) {
        this.nums = nums;
        this.k = k;
        int n = nums.length;
        memo = new Integer[n][k + 1];
        return dfs(0, 1) - 1; // subtract empty subsequence
    }
    
    private int dfs(int i, int product) {
        if (i == nums.length) return 1;
        if (product >= k) return 0;
        if (memo[i][product] != null) return memo[i][product];
        
        int skip = dfs(i + 1, product);
        int take = 0;
        if (product * nums[i] < k) {
            take = dfs(i + 1, product * nums[i]);
        }
        
        memo[i][product] = skip + take;
        return memo[i][product];
    }
}
```

**Key Insight:** Product constraint - prune when product >= k.

